'''Earplay''' is a [[chamber music]] ensemble founded in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] in 1985.<ref>Kosman, Joshua (11 November 2004) [http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/At-20-Earplay-sharp-as-ever-2672909.php "At 20, Earplay sharp as ever"] ''The San Francisco Chronicle''</ref>
They describe their music as "lyrical and ferocious, modern and Romantic, finely honed and accessible." Earplay was founded in 1985 by a consortium of composers and performers. Each year, Earplay presents live concerts of challenging music by contemporary composers, including works commissioned specially for Earplay, which annually sponsors a competition for new compositions. The group's conductor is member [[Mary Chun]], who first appeared as a guest conductor with the group in 1999 (as a guest conductor replacing George Thompson, who conducted the group for 14 years).<ref>Ulrich, Allan (16 November 1999) [http://www.sfgate.com/style/article/Earplay-targets-the-brain-3057963.php "Earplay targets the brain"] ''The San Francisco Chronicle''</ref> Composer [[Martha Callison Horst]] served as President for a number of years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.earplay.org/archives/website/2004/earplay-sf.org/notes052101.html|title=EARPLAY 2001 Program Notes|last=Bennett|first=Richard Festinger, Bruce|website=www.earplay.org|access-date=2018-01-09}}</ref> The current President is Stephen Ness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.earplay.org/archives/doc/2011/email/e110915.pdf|title=Earplay Archives|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
Earplay's presentation of new works is designed to assist composers in their craft and provide recordings for archival purposes. To increase audience involvement, the organization stages pre-concert presentations with composers and discussions of their works.
